  "prompt": "Is money laundering considered a violation of the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is unequivocally a violation of the law in virtually every country. It is criminalized because it enables the concealment of illicit activities (e.g., drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, terrorism financing) by making illegally obtained funds appear legitimate. Key aspects include:\n\n1. **Legal Frameworks**:  \n   - **International**: The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards, and treaties like the UN Convention Against Corruption (UNCAC) obligate countries to criminalize money laundering.  \n   - **National Laws**: Examples include the U.S. Bank Secrecy Act, Money Laundering Control Act (1986), and the EU\u2019s Anti-Money Laundering Directives. Countries like the UK have the Proceeds of Crime Act (2002), and India has the Prevention of Money Laundering Act (2002).  \n\n2. **Stages of Money Laundering**:  \n   - **Placement**: Introducing \"dirty\" money into the financial system (e.g., through cash deposits).  \n   - **Layering**: Complex transactions to obscure the money\u2019s origin (e.g., wire transfers, shell companies).  \n   - **Integration**: Using the laundered funds as \"clean\" money in legal investments or purchases.  \n   Each stage is illegal, even if the perpetrator didn\u2019t commit the original crime (e.g., \"self-laundering\").  \n\n3. **Penalties**:  \n   - Severe fines, imprisonment (often decades in serious cases), asset forfeiture, and reputational damage.  \n   - Institutions (e.g., banks) may face regulatory sanctions for compliance failures.  \n\n4. **Global Enforcement**:  \n   - Even jurisdictions with historically lax laws (e.g., tax havens) face pressure to comply with FATF standards or risk being \"blacklisted,\" harming their financial systems.  \n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious criminal offense worldwide, targeting the financial infrastructure that supports broader criminal enterprises. Laws aim to disrupt illicit economies and promote transparency in financial systems.",
